1pt;text-align:center;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:14pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">Reconciliation of GAAP and Non-GAAP Financial Measures</font></td></tr></table></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Asset Impairments</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded an other-than-temporary impairment charge of $96&#160;million related to an equity method investee in Russia.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Strategic Realignment</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">In August 2020, the company announced strategic steps to transform our organizational structure in an effort to better enable us to capture growth in the fast-changing marketplace. The company has transformed into a networked global organization comprised of operating units, category leads, platform services and the center. The operating units are highly interconnected with more consistency in their structure and a focus on eliminating duplication of resources and scaling new products more quickly. The global marketing category leadership teams primarily focus on innovation as well as marketing efficiency and effectiveness. The center provides strategy, governance and scale for global initiatives. The operating units, global marketing category leadership teams, and the center are supported by platform services, which focuses on providing efficient and scaled global services and capabilities including, but not limited to, governance, transactional work, data management, consumer analytics, digital commerce and social&#47;digital hubs. During the three months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded charges of $1&#160;million, primarily related to revisions to estimated costs accrued in the prior year. During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded net charges of $58&#160;million and $205&#160;million, respectively, primarily related to severance costs and pension settlement charges associated with our strategic realignment initiatives. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Productivity and Reinvestment</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded charges of $19&#160;million and $29&#160;million, respectively. During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded charges of $22&#160;million and $40&#160;million, respectively. The costs incurred were primarily related to certain initiatives designed to further simplify and standardize our organization. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Equity Investees</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded net charges of $35&#160;million and $30&#160;million, respectively. During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded net charges of $60&#160;million and $23&#160;million, respectively. These amounts represent the company&#8217;s proportionate share of significant operating and nonoperating items recorded by certain of our equity method investees.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Transaction Gains&#47;Losses</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded charges of $917&#160;million and $939&#160;million, respectively, related to the remeasurement of our contingent consideration liability to fair value in conjunction with our acquisition of fairlife, LLC (&#8220;fairlife&#8221;) in 2020. Additionally, during the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recognized gains of $26&#160;million and $38&#160;million, respectively, related to the sale of a portion of our ownership interest in an unconsolidated bottling operation. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded a net loss of $24&#160;million as a result of one of our equity method investees issuing additional shares of its stock.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded a net gain, including transaction costs, of $694&#160;million related to the sale of our ownership interest in Coca-Cola Amatil Limited, an equity method investee. Additionally, during the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded charges of $247&#160;million and $251&#160;million, respectively, related to the remeasurement of our contingent consideration liability to fair value in conjunction with our acquisition of fairlife.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Other Items</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Economic (Non-Designated) Hedges</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The company uses derivatives as economic hedges primarily to mitigate the foreign exchange risk for certain currencies, certain interest rate risk, and the price risk associated with the purchase of materials used in our manufacturing processes as well as the purchase of vehicle fuel. Although these derivatives were not designated and&#47;or did not qualify for hedge </font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">17</font></div></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:121.5pt;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:center"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:center"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:center"><table style="border-collapse:collapse;display:inline-table;margin-bottom:5pt;vertical-align:text-bottom;width:98.684%"><tr><td style="width:1.0%"></td><td style="width:98.900%"></td><td style="width:0.1%"></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3" style="padding:2px 1pt;text-align:center;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:15pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">THE COCA-COLA COMPANY AND SUBSIDIARIES</font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3" style="padding:2px 1pt;text-align:center;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:14pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">Reconciliation of GAAP and Non-GAAP Financial Measures</font></td></tr></table></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">accounting, they are effective economic hedges. The changes in fair values of these economic hedges are immediately recognized in earnings. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The company excludes the net impact of mark-to-market adjustments for outstanding hedges and realized gains&#47;losses for settled hedges from our non-GAAP financial information until the period in which the underlying exposure being hedged impacts our consolidated statement of income. Management believes this adjustment provides meaningful information related to the impact of our economic hedging activities. During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the net impact of the company&#8217;s adjustment related to our economic hedging activities resulted in increases of $157&#160;million and $11&#160;million, respectively, to our non-GAAP income before income taxes.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the net impact of the company&#8217;s adjustment related to our economic hedging activities resulted in decreases of $136&#160;million and $15&#160;million, respectively, to our non-GAAP income before income taxes.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Unrealized Gains and Losses on Equity and Trading Debt Securities</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The company excludes the net impact of unrealized gains and losses resulting from mark-to-market adjustments on our equity and trading debt securities from our non-GAAP financial information until the period in which the underlying securities are sold and the associated gains or losses are realized. Management believes this adjustment provides meaningful information related to the impact of our investments in equity and trading debt securities. During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the net impact of the company&#8217;s adjustment related to unrealized gains and losses on our equity and trading debt securities resulted in increases of $293&#160;million and $423&#160;million, respectively, to our non-GAAP income before income taxes.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the net impact of the company&#8217;s adjustment related to unrealized gains and losses on our equity and trading debt securities resulted in decreases of $181&#160;million and $306&#160;million, respectively, to our non-GAAP income before income taxes. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Extinguishment of Long-Term Debt</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded charges of $592&#160;million and $650&#160;million, respectively, related to the extinguishment of long-term debt.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Other</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded net charges of $11&#160;million and $23&#160;million, respectively, related to restructuring our manufacturing operations in the United States. Additionally, during the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded net charges of $13&#160;million and $8&#160;million, respectively, related to the BODYARMOR acquisition in the prior year, which included various transition and transaction costs, employee retention costs and the amortization of noncompete agreements, net of the reimbursement of distributor termination fees. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded charges of $16&#160;million and $35&#160;million, respectively, related to restructuring our manufacturing operations in the United States. During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company also recorded charges of $4&#160;million and $13&#160;million, respectively, related to tax litigation. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Certain Tax Matters </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded $12&#160;million and $66&#160;million, respectively, of excess tax benefits associated with the company&#8217;s stock-based compensation arrangements. During the three months ended July&#160;1, 2022, the company recorded net income tax expense of $4&#160;million associated with return to provision adjustments. </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">During the three and six months ended July&#160;2, 2021, the company recorded $9&#160;million and $30&#160;million, respectively, of excess tax benefits associated with the company&#8217;s stock-based compensation arrangements. style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:11pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;text-decoration:underline">About The Coca-Cola Company</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:115%">The Coca-Cola Company (NYSE&#58; KO) is a total beverage company with products sold in more than 200 countries and territories. Our company&#8217;s purpose is to refresh the world and make a difference. We sell multiple billion-dollar brands across several beverage categories worldwide. Our portfolio of sparkling soft drink brands includes        Coca-Cola, Sprite and Fanta. Our hydration, sports, coffee and tea brands include Dasani, smartwater, vitaminwater, Topo Chico, BODYARMOR, Powerade, Costa, Georgia, Gold Peak and Ayataka. Our nutrition, juice, dairy and plant-based beverage brands include Minute Maid, Simply, innocent, Del Valle, fairlife and AdeS. We&#8217;re constantly transforming our portfolio, from reducing sugar in our drinks to bringing innovative new products to market. We seek to positively impact people&#8217;s lives, communities and the planet through water replenishment, packaging recycling, sustainable sourcing practices and carbon emissions reductions across our value chain. Together with our bottling partners, we employ more than 700,000 people, helping bring economic opportunity to local communities worldwide. Learn more at www.coca-colacompany.com and follow us on Twitter, Instagram, Facebook and LinkedIn.</font></div><div style="height:42.75pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">30</font></div></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:42.75pt;width:100%"><div><font><br></font></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:11pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;text-decoration:underline">Forward-Looking Statements</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">This press release may contain statements, estimates or projections that constitute &#8220;forward-looking statements&#8221; as defined under U.S. federal securities laws. Generally, the words &#8220;believe,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;intend,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;anticipate,&#8221; &#8220;project,&#8221; &#8220;will&#8221; and similar expressions identify forward-looking statements, which generally are not historical in nature. Forward-looking statements are subject to certain risks and uncertainties that could cause The Coca-Cola Company&#8217;s actual results to differ materially from its historical experience and our present expectations or projections. These risks include, but are not limited to, the negative impacts of, and continuing uncertainties associated with the scope, severity and duration of the global COVID-19 pandemic and any resurgences of the pandemic, including the number of people contracting the virus, the impact of shelter-in-place and social distancing requirements, the impact of governmental actions across the globe to contain the virus, vaccine availability, rates of vaccination, the effectiveness of vaccines against existing and new variants of the virus, governmental or other vaccine mandates and potential associated business and supply chain disruptions, and the substance and pace of the post-pandemic economic recovery&#59; direct or indirect negative impacts of the conflict between Russia and Ukraine&#59; an inability to realize the economic benefits from our productivity initiatives, including our reorganization and related strategic realignment initiatives&#59; an inability to attract or retain a highly skilled and diverse workforce&#59; increased competition&#59; an inability to renew collective bargaining agreements on satisfactory terms, or we or our bottling partners experience strikes, work stoppages, labor shortages or labor unrest&#59; an inability to be successful in our innovation activities&#59; changes in the retail landscape or the loss of key retail or foodservice customers&#59; an inability to expand operations in emerging and developing markets&#59; increased cost, disruption of supply or shortage of energy or fuel&#59; inflationary pressures&#59; increased cost, disruption of supply or shortage of ingredients, other raw materials, packaging materials, aluminum cans and other containers&#59; an inability to successfully manage new product launches&#59; obesity and other health-related concerns&#59; evolving consumer product and shopping preferences&#59; product safety and quality concerns&#59; perceived negative health consequences of certain ingredients, such as non-nutritive sweeteners and biotechnology-derived substances, and of other substances present in our beverage products or packaging materials&#59; damage to our brand image, corporate reputation and social license to operate from negative publicity, whether or not warranted, concerning product safety or quality, workplace and human rights, obesity or other issues&#59; an inability to maintain good relationships with our bottling partners&#59; deterioration in our bottling partners&#8217; financial condition&#59; an inability to successfully integrate and manage consolidated bottling operations or other acquired businesses or brands&#59; an inability to successfully manage our refranchising activities&#59; increases in income tax rates, changes in income tax laws or the unfavorable resolution of tax matters, including the outcome of our ongoing tax dispute or any related disputes with the U.S. Internal Revenue Service (&#8220;IRS&#8221;)&#59; the possibility that the assumptions used to calculate our estimated aggregate incremental tax and interest liability related to the potential unfavorable outcome of the ongoing tax dispute with the IRS could significantly change&#59; increased or new indirect taxes in the United States and throughout the world&#59; changes in laws and regulations relating to beverage containers and packaging&#59; significant additional labeling or warning requirements or limitations on the marketing or sale of our products&#59; litigation or legal proceedings&#59; conducting business in markets with high-risk legal compliance environments&#59; failure to adequately protect, or disputes relating to, trademarks, formulae and other intellectual property rights&#59; changes in, or failure to comply with, the laws and regulations applicable to our products or our business operations&#59; fluctuations in foreign currency exchange rates&#59; interest rate increases&#59; unfavorable general economic conditions in the United States and international markets&#59; an inability to achieve our overall long-term growth objectives&#59; default by or failure of one or more of our counterparty financial institutions&#59; impairment charges&#59; failure to realize a significant portion of the anticipated benefits of our strategic relationship with Monster Beverage Corporation&#59; an inability to protect our information systems against service interruption, misappropriation of data or breaches of security&#59; failure to comply with personal data protection and privacy laws&#59; failure to digitize the Coca-Cola system&#59; failure by our third-party service providers and business partners to satisfactorily fulfill their commitments and responsibilities&#59; failure to achieve our environmental, social and governance goals or accurately report our progress due to operational, financial, legal and other risks, many of which are outside our control and are dependent on the actions of our bottling partners and other third parties&#59; increasing concerns about the environmental impact of plastic bottles and other packaging materials&#59; water scarcity and poor quality&#59; increased demand for food products and decreased agricultural productivity&#59; climate change and legal or regulatory responses thereto&#59; adverse weather conditions&#59; and other risks discussed in our filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#8220;SEC&#8221;), including our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&#160;31, 2021 and our subsequently filed Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q, which filings are available from the SEC. <a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display: none;"><p>Reference 1: http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/presentationRef<br> -Publisher SEC<br> -Name Securities Act<br> -Number 230<br> -Section 425<br></p></div>

e.removeAttribute('id');a.parentNode.appendChild(e)}}
if(e)e.style.display='block';Show.LastAR=e};Show.hideAR=function(){Show.LastAR.style.display='none'};Show.toggleNext=function(a){var e=a;while(e.nodeName!='DIV')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e.style){}else if(!e.style.display){}else{var d,p_;if(e.style.display=='none'){d='block';p='-'}else{d='none';p='+'}
